segments.text: Testing, one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, testing, testing, ABC.
Testing number two, testing number two, testing number two, stop.
Testing on Wednesday, Wednesday, Wednesday, testing, testing.
Yes, this is Kay Goldman, class of 68.
All right, Kay, to introduce yourself to anyone that would hear the tape or read transcription, give us a brief biographical summary.
Born, growing up, where'd you go to high school, what did mom and dad do?
All right.
Tell us about yourself, too, that got to A&M.
I was born in Shreveport, Louisiana.
For the first seven years of my life, I lived north of Shreveport in a rural area.
At seven, I moved to Shreveport and lived there until I was 18.
My father
was in the oil business, did all kinds of things.
He was a pumper, a driller.
He was an independent oilman later on.
And I went to Bird High School in Shreveport, Louisiana, which was a very large high school.
There were 800 in my graduating class.
In the summer after my graduation, I married an Aggie who was, at that time,
in his entering his last year in vet school.
And I entered A&M as the wife of a student.
And that's the fall of?
And my parents let me get married because they had changed
the rules so that I could go to school.
As long as I could go to college and we could get married, so that was it.
Your husband, was he a Shreveport area boy?
Yes, he was.
Okay.
And when you all came over here, what did you bring with you?
A carload of clothes and some pots and pans and we moved into Hensel apartment, T1C Hensel.
apartment.

We came a week before school started because we had gotten married on the 30th of August and school at that time didn't start as early as it does now and I needed to take I believe some placement tests here.
I had already taken the SAT and was admitted.
I'm not even sure whether they even looked at my SAT scores or not.
But I had taken the SAT as a junior and could have gotten into the University of Texas, so I know I could have gotten in on my academics.
But that was what we came over pretty much without very much.
My husband was here being paid for by the Louisiana as a vet student.
Did you bring furniture?
Did you rent it?
Well, Hensel was furnished.
I didn't know that.
Yes, Hensel was furnished.

And the one thing that I realized after we got here was there were no curtains and there were blinds, but if you pulled the blinds open, then you didn't have any window coverings, so my mom made window coverings.
We had a few pieces, but not, mostly it was furnished, so we didn't bring furniture.
And this was, describe what it physically, the dimensions of the apartment.
It was brown.
Everything in it was brown.
It had a brown floor.
The living dining area was probably about 22 feet in length and maybe 12 feet in width.
The kitchen, I think, probably I could have touched every single wall by stretching out my arms.
And the bedroom area was a nice size bedroom area and the bathroom area.
I couldn't guess how large it was.
Some couples even had washers and dryers in their... One bedroom?
One bedroom apartment, yes.
We had a lot of, it was in 64, and we had a lot of returning servicemen who were living over there who actually, they lived in the front half of the apartment and they had children in the bedroom.
It wasn't a bad place to live.
The kitchen, for a place that has both engineering and architecture, the
The kitchen was just terrible, though.
There was no ventilation.
And I've talked to other people, and if you cooked or fried, you had to open the doors and the windows because there was no ventilation in the kitchen at all.
And no air conditioning, of course.
No, but we did have an air conditioning unit.
You could add your own air conditioning.
A window unit?
A window unit.
And the apartment, if I remember correctly, the rent was $65 a month.
And that included your utilities.
But if you had a window unit, then you paid additional electric bill.
And I don't remember exactly what the electric bill ran.
Our air conditioning unit would usually cool the front room and maybe some of the bedroom.
When it was very hot, we would sleep in the living room.
Now, in terms of enrolling and so forth, you made all of the arrangements to be admitted in advance.
Yes, I did.
Did you come over here to visit during any of those?
Not specifically for enrollment purposes.
My former husband made all those arrangements with the university himself and I had my transcripts and everything sent from my high school.

The one thing that was rather unusual, and I assume because they hadn't been used to dealing with women who were in the process of getting married, they asked my husband if the transcripts could be sent under my married name.
And of course the high school is going, but you're not married yet.
We're going to send them under your maiden name.
And so he had to explain to whoever was going to receive them that they were going to come under a different name and that they would have to match them up.
Okay, when you got over here, describe registration and so forth.

Well, the first thing I had to do was take a placement test and then I was assigned a professor and at a certain time and we went to, I went to his office and along with probably eight or ten other freshman guys,

and we sat outside the hall and of course this room wasn't air conditioned and the windows were open and the doors were open and I believe the gentleman was an engineering professor and I could hear the preceding students going in and he would talk to them about what their major was

And if they mentioned anything about engineering or mathematics, he was always, you know, why don't you take German and I think you need to take this class and these are the other classes that you need to take.
And so I could hear him proceed with the ones that were ahead of me.
When I got into his office, he just kind of looked up and then he motioned for me to sit down and he said, what do you want to register for?
And when I told him what the classes I wanted to register for, and it did not include German, it did include a math, and basically it was math, English, and history.
And he said, fine.
And that was it.
He didn't make any comments at all about what I should take, what I shouldn't take.
I do know that if I had asked to take
a P.E.
class, there was the only thing that we could take was bowling.
And I am not even sure that they were set up for us to sign up for bowling until the next semester.
But we could not, there were no P.E.
classes at all for the women.
Right.
In those sessions, were you the only female?
Yes, I was.
There were no, I never saw, generally, because I was a freshman, I didn't see a lot of other females either.
in counseling or in classes.
As far as you were aware, was this the first fall women were?
I was under the impression that it was the first fall that they had announced that.
I think that's right.
That the, although I did look at a book recently that said that there were women that came in 93, I mean in 63, but I was under the impression that this was the first fall where there was an official
acceptance policy and we had to prove, I had to bring my marriage license, and we had to prove that I was married to a student, to a registered student before I could enroll.
Did you overhear as you walked down the hallway or anything those first two or three days going through these sessions, did you hear any comments, any
I never heard any kind of comments directed either specifically at me or indirectly at me, either in the first few days or later on.
Not only did I not have any comments, but I was generally well received and I had a couple of times when some of the other Aggies, the male Aggies,
did some very good deeds to help me.
Now, in those first few days, what did you, how did you dress?
What did you wear?
I was pretty formal in my dress, primarily because I tended to be more formal.
Generally I wore, I always wore a dress or skirt and blouse.
And a lot of times I did wear flats, but there were a lot of times where I also wore stockings to class.
So I was more dressed up than what you would normally expect a student to wear.
But I did wear stockings often.
All right, then as classes began, do you remember you took full load?
No, I only took nine hours.
Nine hours, all right.
And share what you remember about that first semester.
It was very interesting because not only was I in experiment, but A&M was experimenting and taking classes, large sections of classes and having lectures in math and in English.

that were geared for 100 or 120 students and then dividing those students up into discussion sessions one day or one day a week or perhaps two, I can't remember, but I know both my math and my English class was set up that way.
So that was an experiment.
So I was dealing, I was an experiment and I was dealing with classes that hadn't been, you know, they hadn't been, no,
The professors were usually pretty friendly.

I do know that I took a history class in Nagel and I would get there early so that often I could hear the classes ahead of me because we could hear them through the transoms even if they had the door closed.
Often, as I'm sure the professors might have done in an all-male school, they had
off-color stories that they shared with the students and so I was outside the door one early in the class in the session and I had heard the story.
I had heard him tell the story at an appropriate time, the historian, and then I went in and I was the only female in the class and when he
presented his lecture, he presented the same lecture again.

But when he got to that point where he was going to tell this story, he looked directly at me, he paused, he waited a few minutes, and then went on without telling the story, without telling the story.
But the students, the fellow students were friendly in the classes.
I wasn't asked to study groups or anything like that.
But they spoke to me and talked to me and chatted just like you would with a student any other time before class or after class or I didn't understand this or what did you get out of that.
How many other young coeds did you see?
That first semester there were no other coeds in any of my classes.
You would see a couple of, you would see a few women around the campus, but generally it was hard to tell whether these were truly students or whether they were young,
staff members or secretaries or things like that if you just saw them walking around.
But I, in that first semester, had no other females in my class.
And academically, how did things go?
Well, English gave me some problems, math I made a very good grade in.
I believe at that time the A&M grading system was a little bit different also.
And I made a very good grade in both math and history, but English I was having problems with.
Any of those teachers now, in retrospect, were any of those first instructors important?
The math professor I had, and I took this class, he lectured in the Animal Industries building in the large lecture room, and I sat on the front row to the right, and I was, we were engaged.

the two of us often and I ask a lot of questions and would go to his office occasionally and I believe he was the head of the department of the math department at that time and he commented about my questions and he was a help later on when I the next during the next semester I don't remember anybody's name particularly but I did I did do well in the in the history class also so
As you walked down the sidewalk, did the Aggies greet you appropriately?
Howdy, good morning, that sort of thing?
Generally, they did.
Yes, they did.
And they were, it was always friendly.
It was always howdy or, yes, howdy.
It's generally the way I got credit.
Yeah.
Your husband was in vet school.
Yes, he was.
So, did you walk from Hensel over to the campus?
No, I, we had a car and I would drop him off and then I would generally park in the area where that Reed, the Reed Annex, the G. Raleigh-White is now.
And so, I would park in that area and then go to class and then leave class.
My classes were dispersed and were all through the morning and I would go pick him up for lunch because at that time,
the university didn't hold classes during the lunch hour.
So then I would get him and we would have lunch together and then I would take him to school.
Where'd you eat lunch?
Generally at home, I mean in the Hensel apartments.
It was, it didn't take very long unless there was a train.
And did you have that lunch fixed in advance or did you
A lot of times what we did was we had leftovers, and I would cook something that was big enough so that we could have leftovers.
We had sandwiches sometimes.
The first week before school started, I had never cooked before.
I came from a family that had a maid, and my husband, we're regressing here, but my husband decided that we should go watch the football team practice.
and I put dinner in the oven and we went over and the football practice was open and we could watch them in the football stadium.
I lost track of time and poked him in the ribs and said,
We have to go now.
By the time we got back to our apartment, our dinner was duly burnt up.
The roast was ruined.
But generally, I fixed a chicken or a roast or something so we could have a quick lunch.
Do you have any recollection as to how much your fees were then?
By what did it cost?
I don't remember at all how much the fees were.
I knew that we paid $65 for an apartment and that we figured that we could probably eat on maybe $15 to $20 a week for food.
My husband's uniforms that he wore at the vet school, we allowed something like $15 a month for those to be laundered.

and our gas bill our gasoline bill not our gas bill our gasoline bill ran about 10 or 12 dollars a month describe the typical class day routine what time did you all get up and what did you do when and when did you go to bed we were usually up by 6 or 6 30 in the morning i cooked breakfast i cooked three meals a day or fixed something three for three meals a day and then we would leave the apartment of around

740 or 745 and I would take him to whichever building in the vet school that he was needed to be in and then drive right back over and park but usually that semester I had a nine o'clock class I did not have an eight o'clock class then I went to class I guess nine ten and eleven or nine ten and anyway somewhere around noon I finished
and I would drop back over to the vet school, pick him up, and we would go home and have lunch.

If I needed to do something, then I would take him back to the vet school and drop him off, and then I would go grocery shopping or do whatever else I needed to do and pick him up at 5 o'clock when he finished.
There were some times when he was doing rotations that he didn't finish at 5 o'clock, but generally I would pick him up at 5 o'clock, we would go back to the apartment,
and I would serve dinner, usually around 6 o'clock.
We both would then study.
Sometimes he went back to the vet school.
That was not often, but sometimes he needed to do that.
Probably around 10.30 we were finished for the day and we were in bed around 10.30 or 11.
There were Saturday classes then in those days.
I didn't have any.
You didn't?
No, no.
He worked on Saturday because the vet school had responsibilities that were on Saturday.
What did you all do for diversions?
Well, during the fall semester we went to almost every single football game.
And we went to all the away games except one, and I believe that was the Texas Tech game.
I don't remember.
It might not have been.
Texas Tech might have played here.
We drove to Baton Rouge with three of his friends in our car.
And we got to Baton Rouge early in the afternoon.
And he and his friends were staying in the ZBT fraternity house.
and I was staying in the dorms with a friend of mine.
We deposited our things, then we went and found something to eat and went to the football game.
Everybody was, you know, in high spirits.
When we got there, by the time the football game was over and we lost to LSU,

uh... his buddies were very in a very sour mood we all met back at the ZBT house and about twelve thirty he came to me and said the guys want to leave because we weren't going to leave until sunday morning and uh... so i had to go find my friend who had the key to her dorm room so that i could get my clothes back and my luggage which wasn't easy i just i had to find her
Sometime later, probably around 1 or 1.30, we all piled back in the car and drove back towards College Station.
We took turns driving.
My turn came sometime around 4 o'clock in the morning.
Everybody else in the car was asleep.
So much for chivalry, I guess.
I was driving the early morning shift.
And it was foggy, but somehow.
I was afraid I'd gotten turned around, but we got back home.
And we dropped his friends off.
And I was very unhappy about the whole evening and about being tired.
So instead of going back to the apartment and eating breakfast, we went to Coach's.
We had breakfast at Coach's and then went back to the apartment.
What was your, at your first Aggie football game, what was your impression?
Well, I had actually been to several football games before that year.
In fact, while my husband, my former husband and I were dating, he had come home and the Shreveport Hometown Club used to take a train from the station in Shreveport down to LSU
And we rode, and you would get on the train Friday evening and ride all night down to LSU.
And we went to that game.
So I had actually been to LSU before.
I had met him in Dallas for several games.
So I'd been at football games before.
stood on the, you know, watched the parade in downtown Dallas or Fort Worth.
And you knew about yell practices and things like that.
Yes, yes, I knew about all that.
Were there any things about that first fall at A&M that surprised you?
Anything that surprised me?
I guess everything was so new that I was just accepting everything that went, you know, with being here.
How long before you all made some friends over in, with other couples over in the student housing area?
We made a few friends right away and, but actually a lot of our friends were his either

uh couples that he knew from vet school several there were a couple of those and um and couples that we met because we were both jewish and we met them at the hill el foundation in fact i in fact i i know one couple from vet school who's here now and that's um
Bubba Watek and his wife.
We lived in Hensel together.
Oh, I know Bubba.
Marvelous person.
Yes.
Is he the same vintage?
Yes.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Yes.
The reason I said, oh, I would like you to share any and all that you can about the Jewish part of the student body here.
We don't know much about that.
Right.
At that time, the students were generally excused on Wednesday night for religious services.

And I have no idea whether they were forced to leave the dorms or they were encouraged to leave the dorms or exactly, but most of the students left the dorms on Wednesday night and the Jewish students would go to the Hillel on Wednesday night.
We didn't have services, but we would get together.
We would do things like play bridge and that kind of, or just sit over there and talk.
And the.
And this would be what, a couple of dozen?
Generally about 12 or maybe more.
It depended on when in the semester it was, what was going on, other times.
The other things that happened was on Friday night when the services were held, almost all the Jewish students would come to services
Sometimes we would even have meals over there on Friday nights because all the students were living on campus.
If somebody cooked a meal off campus, they were really excited about getting to eat something other than from Sabisa or Duncan or.
And where the, in terms of hometowns, where were most of these youngsters from?
Almost all of them were from Texas.
Were they urban or small town?
Yes, the ones that were here then I would say were primarily
urban, Dallas, Houston, San Antonio, although there were others from Baytown or from some of the smaller towns.
We didn't have that many students from tiny towns, although that I do know that sometime during that time there were two boys from Alice and their last name was Shinus.
Right now their first names escape me, but I do know them and I know their mother as a matter of fact.
But they came from Alice and so I'm sure Alice qualifies as a tiny town.
And who conducted the services in those days?
There was no rabbi here and Frank Kahn and Saul Klein generally conducted the services.
with the aid of whoever else was here that was knowledgeable enough to help conduct the services.
But they were usually the leaders and then the students would also participate.
But they were the ones, the two that did lead the services every Friday night and on the holidays.
Do you remember anything relative to your background?
Do you remember anything happening that was shocking or inappropriate or?
No, nothing ever happened.
The religion hardly ever came up in class or on the campus.
It was a time when people believed that religion was a private issue and I don't believe that it was
We didn't have proselytizing on the campus and I really believe that people, unless you were a very close friend of someone, you didn't bring up that subject.
It's not that religion didn't matter, it was just considered a personal issue and not an issue to be talked about.
I do know one time in a class for some, I think it was a world history class, the professor asked,

you know a show of hands of how many people it could have been American history but I don't remember but how many people were various religions and then he he said well what's left and there were two of us that raised our hand and both of us happened to be Jewish so that was a kind of unusual thing but but that's the only thing because he hadn't called out he hadn't asked for Jewish hands but he just assumed that there probably weren't any Jews in the class
And, but never, I was never even, nobody ever asked anything about that or said anything.
So you're saying no incidents or?
No incidents.
As far as I can remember or would be aware of, there was never anything that happened.
Okay, on you and your husband and friends, if y'all wanted to have a good time, what'd you do?

Well because we were all students we were all on limited budgets and we usually entertained in our own homes and we did not generally invite each other over for a meal because that was probably a budget breaker but often we would have people over at 8.30 or 8 o'clock and we would serve dessert and coffee and we would sit and we sometimes played games
but generally would just sit around and talk.
If these were couples from the vet school, generally it was about school or the, you know, the vet school issues.
And, but if there were other couples, it was just a variety of different subjects.
And, but we very, we didn't entertain or we didn't have, we spent our discretionary money
I think going to the football games rather than doing anything else like having a good time out other than our homes.
Did you meet Dean Al Price?
No, I didn't meet any of the The Ratonier faculty?
Right, right.
Oh, wait a minute, let's see, Price.
No, I didn't know him.
I probably did, but I don't know him.
I probably met him.
And in that fall, as far as you know, did everybody attend class pretty regularly?
Yes.
I think we were all so afraid that it would affect our grades, we were all, you know, we didn't skip class and things like that.
And did you sometimes go to the MSC for a cup of coffee or a soft drink?
Right.
We did that occasionally.
One of the other things that we did was the MSC had rooms in the, not in the basement, I think they're in the basement now, but they had pianos in the downstairs under the rooms that they rented.
And my husband played the piano and we would go over there sometimes on Sunday evenings or sometimes and he would
He would play and I would just sit there.
